1. OSI Model (Open Systems Interconnection)

The OSI model explains how data travels from one device to another over a network using 7 layers.

🔹 Layer 1: Physical Layer
Transfers raw bits (0s and 1s)
Uses cables, signals, radio waves
Devices: hubs, cables, repeaters
Example: Ethernet cable sending data
🔹 Layer 2: Data Link Layer
Transfers data between devices in same network
Uses MAC address
Devices: switches, network cards
Example: Wi-Fi sending data to your laptop
🔹 Layer 3: Network Layer
Finds best path for data (routing)
Uses IP address
Devices: routers
Example: Data traveling from India to US server
🔹 Layer 4: Transport Layer
End-to-end delivery of data
Uses TCP or UDP
Example: WhatsApp message delivery, video streaming
🔹 Layer 5: Session Layer
Maintains connection between devices
Controls sessions
Example: Login session in Instagram or Gmail
🔹 Layer 6: Presentation Layer
Converts data format, encryption, compression
Example: HTTPS encryption, image/audio formats
🔹 Layer 7: Application Layer
Interface for users
Example: Chrome, YouTube, Gmail
📌 Real-world OSI Example

When you send a WhatsApp message:

App Layer → WhatsApp app
Transport → TCP/UDP
Network → IP routing
Data Link → Wi-Fi/MAC
Physical → wireless signals
2. TCP/IP Model

This is the real-world internet model.

🔹 Network Access Layer
Combines OSI Layer 1 + 2
Handles hardware + MAC address
🔹 Internet Layer
Uses IP address
Handles routing across networks
🔹 Transport Layer
Uses TCP or UDP
Controls delivery of data
🔹 Application Layer
Web, email, apps
Protocols: HTTP, HTTPS, DNS, FTP
3. TCP (Transmission Control Protocol)
Connection-oriented
Reliable delivery
Data arrives in order
Lost packets are retransmitted
Examples:
Websites
File downloads
Email

👉 Think: “Slow but safe delivery”

4. UDP (User Datagram Protocol)
Connectionless
Fast communication
No guarantee of delivery
No ordering
Examples:
Online gaming
Video streaming
Voice calls

👉 Think: “Fast but not always reliable”

5. Ports

Ports are logical doors used by applications to communicate.

IP address = location
Port = service door
Range:

0 – 65535

6. Common Ports

HTTP → 80 (web browsing)
HTTPS → 443 (secure web)
FTP → 21 (file transfer)
SSH → 22 (remote login)
DNS → 53 (name resolution)
SMTP → 25 (send email)
IMAP → 143 (receive email)

7. DNS (Domain Name System)

DNS is like the internet phonebook.

It converts domain names into IP addresses.

Example:

www.google.com → 142.250.x.x

8. DNS Resolution Flow

When you enter a website:

Browser cache check
OS cache check
Router cache check
ISP DNS resolver
Root DNS server
TLD server (.com / .in)
Authoritative DNS server
IP address returned
Website loads
9. DNS Records
🔹 A Record (Address Record)
Maps domain → IPv4 address

Example:
example.com → 192.168.1.1

👉 Used to point domain to server IP

🔹 CNAME Record (Canonical Name)
Maps one domain to another (alias)

Example:
www.example.com → example.com

👉 Used for subdomains or redirection

🔹 MX Record (Mail Exchange)
Handles email delivery
Points to mail servers

Example:
example.com → mail server

👉 Without MX record, email cannot be received


